The paper investigates game-theoretic approaches for decision making in large-scale and complex systems, which suggests that it belongs to the Game Theory (cs.GT) sub-category. The paper also discusses the use of machine learning techniques, specifically random projection methods, which suggests that it could also belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category. Additionally, the paper deals with optimization and computational challenges, which could place it in the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. The paper also discusses the use of linear transformations and their effect on Nash equilibrium solutions, which suggests that it could belong to the Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-category. Finally, the paper deals with limited information and big data sets, which could place it in the Information Theory (cs.IT) sub-category.
